			</p>

			
			<div class="content">I tried writing a replacement for &quot;dir&quot; because I'm so accustomed to using &quot;ls&quot;. I wrote it successfully in Python, but wanted it to be faster so I decided to write it C++, which I have very limited knowledge in. Here's my code:<br /><dl class="codebox"><dt>Code: <a href="#" onclick="selectCode(this); return false;">Select all</a></dt><dd><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;<br />#include &lt;string&gt;<br /><br />using namespace std;<br /><br />void usage();<br />void version();<br /><br />void version()<br />{<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; endl;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; &quot;VERSION : 0.1 BETA\n&quot;;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; &quot;AUTHOR&nbsp; : the0nlyb0ss\n&quot;;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; &quot;DATE&nbsp; &nbsp; : 10/2/2010\n&quot;;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; &quot;OS&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; : Windows\n&quot;;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; endl;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; &quot;LS.EXE was created as a 'dir' subsitute for all us UNIX lovers out there.\n&quot;;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; &quot;It takes a few of the common argv for 'ls' such as '-l' and '-a'.\n&quot;;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; endl;<br />}&nbsp; &nbsp;<br /><br />void usage()<br />{<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; endl;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; &quot;USAGE: ls &lt;options&gt; &lt;folder&gt;&quot; &lt;&lt; endl &lt;&lt; endl;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\t-h&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;: Show this help text&quot; &lt;&lt; endl;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\t-v&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;: Show version and program info&quot; &lt;&lt; endl;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\t-l&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;: Show files with owner information&quot; &lt;&lt; endl;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\t-a&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;: Show only hidden files&quot; &lt;&lt; endl;<br />}<br /><br />int main(int argc, char* argv&#91;&#93;)<br />{<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;if(argc &lt; 1 || argc &gt; 3){<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;usage();<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;if(argc == 1){<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;system(&quot;DIR&quot;);<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;if(argv&#91;1&#93; == &quot;-h&quot;){<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;usage();<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;else if(argv&#91;1&#93; == &quot;-v&quot;){<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;version();<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;else if(argv&#91;1&#93; == &quot;-l&quot;){<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;system(&quot;DIR /Q&quot;);<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;else if(argv&#91;1&#93; == &quot;-a&quot;){<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;system(&quot;DIR /A:H&quot;);<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;else if(argv&#91;1&#93; == &quot;-la&quot;){<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;system(&quot;DIR /A:H /Q&quot;);<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;return 0;<br />}<br /></code></dd></dl><br /><br />The program works fine when I simply type &quot;ls&quot;, and it also gives me the usage() function when I type more than 3 arguments, but when I try typing any valid arguments, whether it's &quot;-h&quot;, &quot;-a&quot;, &quot;-l&quot;, &quot;-v&quot;, or &quot;-la&quot;, it doesn't do anything at all.</div>

